BT 1 0 0 1 0 135 Tm 12 TL /F1 9 Tf 0 0 0 rg (You can make a car run on water. Not a metaphor. Not a scam. Not perpetual motion. Real chemistry, real engineering,) Tj T* (demonstrated in labs at MIT and Purdue. The mechanism: aluminum-gallium alloy pellets dropped into ordinary water) Tj T* (produce hydrogen gas at room temperature, on demand, with no electrolysis and no external energy input at the point of) Tj T* (use. The gallium disrupts aluminum's oxide layer, exposing fresh metal that splits water spontaneously -- 2Al + 6H?O -) Tj (>) Tj T* (2Al\(OH\)? + 3H?. The hydrogen feeds a PEM fuel cell that drives the wheels. The gallium is not consumed -- it is recovered) Tj T* (and reused. The aluminum hydroxide byproduct is recyclable back to aluminum. The water is the fuel. The aluminum is the) Tj T* (battery. This paper presents a complete vehicle architecture combining the aluminum-water reaction \(Woodall, 2007;) Tj T* -0.094167 Tw (Amberchan et al., JACS 2022\) with PEM fuel cell technology \(Toyota Mirai, 128 kW demonstrated\) and the Wike Coherence) Tj T* 0 Tw (framework for optimizing the reaction at the molecular level. We compute that a 60 kg aluminum-gallium fuel cartridge with) Tj T* (40 liters of water provides 500+ km range at highway speeds. The fuel cost is the energy to recycle aluminum --) Tj T* (approximately $0.04-0.06/km using renewable electricity, competitive with gasoline. No high-pressure hydrogen tanks. No) Tj T* (charging infrastructure. No grid dependency at point of use. Fill the water tank. Drop in a cartridge. Drive.) Tj T* ET
